ranslations of writings from the last years of Jacques Derrida’s lifeCollects Derrida’s later thoughts on topics including writing, racism and his school lifeEnglish-language translations of previously untranslated essays and interviewsProvides further insight into the thinker’s relationships with contemporary figuresContributes significantly to our understanding of Derrida’s work in politics, literary theory and philosophyIn two volumes, Geoffrey Bennington and Kas Saghafi present the majority of Jacques Derrida’s untranslated, and previously uncollected, essays and interviews. Dating mostly from 1992 to 2004, these writings offer a fuller picture of Derrida’s biography, theoretical engagements and the stakes of his social and political investments. Institutions, Inventions, and Inscriptions by Jacques Derrida: Thinking What Comes, Volume 2 collects Derrida’s writings on friends including Emmanuel Levinas, Alain David, Louis Marin, Marie-Louise Mallet, Safaa Fathy, Mathieu Bénézet and Jos Joliet. It also features interviews that illuminate his experience at school, his writing habits, the relation he saw between philosophical discourse to the ‘poetic’, and his views on the singularity of literature and fiction. Whether writing about racism and anti-Semitism, filiation and fidelity, or hospitality and responsibility, Derrida is razor-sharp and impassioned. These volumes allow significant insight into his mature thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aPhilosophy, Frenchy20th century. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aBennington, Geoffrey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcQuillan, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaghafi, Kas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator